3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates every hour based on the difference between the perpetual contract price and the oracle-derived index price. Funding payments flow between longs and shorts to keep the perpetual price aligned with the underlying ADA spot price. The exchange uses a GLP liquidity pool model where traders take positions against the pool rather than other traders, making funding rates dependent on overall directional bias and oracle price divergence. Settlement occurs automatically every hour with no manual intervention required."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ADA","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ADA/USDT on GMX presents compelling arbitrage opportunities due to Cardano's position as a major Layer 1 blockchain with significant retail and institutional interest. The hourly funding frequency provides more granular arbitrage windows compared to 8-hour cycles on centralized exchanges. GMX's oracle-based pricing can create temporary divergences from spot markets during volatile periods, particularly beneficial for sophisticated arbitrageurs monitoring multiple venues."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ADA funding rates on GMX have historically shown strong correlation with broader altcoin sentiment and Cardano ecosystem developments. During the 2023 DeFi summer, positive funding rates averaged 0.02-0.05% hourly when ADA outperformed BTC. Network upgrade announcements and major partnership news typically drive sustained positive funding for 24-48 hour periods. Bear market phases often see negative rates as shorts dominate, with funding occasionally reaching -0.08% hourly during major selloffs. The oracle-based model means GMX rates can lag CEX funding by 10-30 minutes during rapid price movements."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-venue arbitrage between GMX and centralized exchanges like Binance or OKX offers the most consistent profits given differing funding frequencies. Long positions on GMX can be hedged with shorts on 8-hour funding CEXs when GMX shows sustained positive rates above 0.03% hourly. Price impact considerations become critical above $50K position sizes due to GLP pool depth limitations. Arbitrageurs should monitor Arbitrum gas costs and bridge delays when executing time-sensitive strategies. The oracle dependency creates unique opportunities during network congestion when price feeds lag spot markets by several minutes."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Oracle risks represent the primary concern as GMX relies on external price feeds that can malfunction or experience delays during extreme volatility. Liquidity constraints in the GLP pool can cause significant price impact on large positions, especially during low-volume periods. Smart contract risks on Arbitrum and potential bridge vulnerabilities when moving funds cross-chain require careful position sizing. Funding rate volatility can swing rapidly from positive to negative within single trading sessions, making timing crucial for profitable arbitrage execution. Gas fee spikes on Arbitrum during network congestion can erode profits on smaller arbitrage positions."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often does GMX settle ADA funding rates compared to other exchanges?","answer":"GMX settles funding rates every hour for all perpetual pairs including ADA/USDT, which is more frequent than the standard 8-hour cycles used by most centralized exchanges. This creates unique arbitrage windows for traders monitoring multiple venues simultaneously."},{"question":"What makes GMX's ADA funding calculation different from order book exchanges?","answer":"GMX uses oracle-based pricing rather than order book dynamics, meaning funding rates reflect divergence between perpetual and oracle prices rather than trader positioning. This can create temporary arbitrage opportunities when oracle feeds lag during volatile ADA price movements."},{"question":"How does GLP pool depth affect large ADA funding rate arbitrage positions?","answer":"Large positions above $50K can experience significant price impact due to GLP pool constraints, potentially eroding arbitrage profits. Traders should monitor real-time pool utilization and consider splitting large positions across multiple transactions or time periods."},{"question":"What are the main risks when arbitraging ADA funding rates on GMX?","answer":"Primary risks include oracle failure or delays during volatility, smart contract risks on Arbitrum, bridge vulnerabilities when moving funds, and potential liquidity constraints in the GLP pool during high utilization periods."}]}]
